The '''Portland Indians''' were a professional  team in .  They were a member of the  for the duration of the league, which only lasted two seasons: 1946–47 and 1947–48. They played their home games in the .<ref name=apbr>{{cite web|url=http://www.apbr.org/pcpbl.html|title=Pacific Coast Professional Basketball League 1946–47 to 1947–48|last=Kenyon|first=J. Michael|accessdate=2007-11-06|publisher=Association for Professional Basketball Research}}</ref>
In the 1946–47 season, the Indians posted the best overall record, but finished second in the round-robin playoffs to the . When the Fircrests declined an invitation to the  in Chicago, the Indians went instead, but lost to the  in the first round.<ref name=apbr/>
In the 1947–48 season, the Indians entered the round-robin playoffs as a wildcard team and ended up winning the championship, defeating the  3 games to 1.<ref name=apbr/>